Meh. Finally dined here again this weekend after my first visit over a decade ago. Friends convinced me to give it another try, and well... meh. I chose the 3 courses for $92 (which is $125 with tax, mandatory health surcharge and tip), and two of my friends ordered the 5 courses with the third friend option for 4 courses. Both of the 5 course orderers had said that the staff usually brings out a little something for the non-course-orderers so you're not just sitting there staring at other people eat. We'll get back to that. I started with the "Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Spring Vegetables and Beech Mushrooms", which my 5-course-ordering friend also had. My dish had zero rock shrimp, two pieces of crab, and a ton of veggies and mushrooms. My friend's dish had many shrimp, 3 pieces of crab, and the veggies and mushrooms too. Weird. Tasty, but frustrated by the lack of shrimp! Second course, I went with the "Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts and Shiitake Mushrooms" (I'm pasting the description from the web site menu but it may not be accurate). I had one miniscule piece of lobster, the tiniest piece of calamari that I've ever seen (seriously the size of my pinky nail), two big mussels, one scallop cut into pieces, and several shrimp, plus a ton of big pieces of lemongrass. This was a decent dish but not stellar, and again confused by the lack of seafood. (My friend's sea scallops dish was much better). Third course, nothing for me but I got fresh silverware for no reason, and just sat there while my friends ate. Very awkward. Fourth course, I got "Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Huckleberry Bordelaise" (again, pasting from the web site but my menu at the restaurant said cherries instead of huckleberry). Outstanding dish. Perfectly cooked duck, and I love the hash. I had this dish last time and loved it then as well. Fifth course, one friend ordered the cheese service and got her cheeses from the cart, and then about a five minute delay before the other two guests got their desserts. The server quite rudely commented this time as he put down my silverware "no dessert for you, but here's some silverware just in case". Gee, thanks. After my friends had almost finished their dishes, a special birthday dessert was brought out for my friend and a small tray of tiny bites for us to share (about nine pieces). Oddly, I saw tables of two people get the same tray - but only one tray for the 4 of us to split. Overall, I was really let down, especially given the large price tag. I was made to feel quite awkward because I didn't order the same number of courses, and I don't understand why I didn't even receive the same quality of dish as my friend. Service was extremely slow, and I really did not appreciate the snide comment about "no dessert for you". I did not raise any issues at the time because this was my friend's birthday dinner, but I won't be returning here (despite that amazing duck dish).

This is not your everyday restaurant. But at the same time, not bad for a special occasion. Went here for a 3rd year wedding anniversary and for two people with wine tasting, I spent close to $500 including tips! Oh they even have us a take home bread pudding which we savoured for breakfast the next morning! What I love about this place is you aren't tied to a pre fix. You are free to choose from a different selection from their menu so it gives it more flexibility for you to order what you want. I remember getting the risotto for appetizer, a white fish for entree and a chocolate soufflé for dessert. Everything was just a party in my mouth. I can't remember the exact names but I did remember how they made me feel. And the customer service is just phenomenal! I am happy to have Gary Danko as one of my very first experience with fine dining! I highly recommend this if you are visiting SF! You can't find them anywhere else.

Always Amazing! Top notch service! Excellent food! Great ambiance! Best restaurant in San Francisco!

This was my second time at Gary Danko and this time my husband surprised me with a dinner here for my birthday. This is more 3.5 stars but I decided to round down to 3 stars. PARKING: We came on a Sunday night around 8pm and there was some decent street parking. I think if you circle around and try to find something you'll be fine. RESERVATIONS: My husband made the reservations but he said he made them about a month in advance and even then he could only get a 8:30 reservation for 2. ATMOSPHERE: Gary Danko has a lot of reviews and supposedly 1 michelin star but the inside is pretty old/traditional looking. Don't expect your super contemporary, trendy atmosphere. It's dark lit, roses on the table, highly attentive waiters and a weird decor ranging from sea theme to jungle? Overall, not the type of atmosphere I particularly like but it's certainly fancy and romantic. FOOD: They have these "set" menus where you can choose whatever you want and pay a set price. For example, if you choose the 3 course dinner you pay $95. You could do whatever you want, which means 3 desserts, 3 appetizers, 3 entrees etc. I would suggest coordinating with your other party so you can all try different items. Their portions aren't huge but aren't super tiny either. You are given an amuse bouche to begin with and then unlimited bread and butter. They also give you a small dessert tray with mini desserts and a take home pastry. So in the end, you're getting more than just the 3 entrees. I'm sure their menu changes all the time so I won't go into specifics but I would say everything we had was good. Nothing mind blowing, nothing bad...just good. I think that's why I decided on 3.5 stars. The price I'm paying and what I was expecting I was hoping for a bit more or something more memorable. Overall, if you like fancy restaurants and the $95 fee per person doesn't shock you then definitely give this place a try.

I'm drooling about the food while writing this review. My bf booked this place in advance for my birthday since I've been wanting to try it in forever. We decided to get the 5 course meal for $135. What's amazing is that you can choose your own five selections from wherever area you want. If you want all meat... you can do all meat. If you want meat, fish, appetizer, dessert, and cheese... you can do that. Rose wine - They only had one rose wine by the glass on the menu. It was a 2017 rose wine from Napa. It was very tasty, and not crazy sweet. Highly recommend. Glazed oysters (appetizer) - Comes with four oysters and cavier in the middle. The sauce pairs extremely well with the oysters and the cavier is a finishing touch. I really enjoyed this appetizer. Dungeness crab salad (appetizer) - The crab was really fresh and the leafy greens were a great light start to the meal. Roast maine lobster (fish and seafood) - If I had known that this was so good, I would've skipped the duck breast and Dungeness crab salad and got three of these. This dish is a definitely must get! You won't regret it. Lemon pepper duck breast (meat and game birds) - To be honest, I'm not a duck person so I have no idea why I got this. They gave a generous portion, and it was cooked nicely. If you like duck, you'd probably appreciate this dish more than I would. Strawberry souffle (dessert) - The top part of this is very tasty, but once you get to the middle, it's mostly sauce and it's too sweet. I'd probably skip dessert next time or try the cookies. Service was beyond impeccable and my plate was never empty of their delicious bread. I think I had 6 pieces which is why I got so full after my third item. Gary Danko is a lovely place, and I'd definitely be back!

Gary Danko provides one of the greatest fine-dining experiences in San Francisco. The chefs and servers are thoughtful and masters at what they do. The way the food is served is like a performance! The restaurant ambiance is dimly lit and very intimate--perfect for any special occasion. I ordered the Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes and Swiss Chard. The filet was topped with blue cheese butter and a sweet marmalade. Let me tell you...this was THE BEST filet that I have ever had in my life! The meat was incredibly flavorful and tender--it cut like butter. I do not regularly enjoy blue cheese, but the combination of flavors with the beef and the sweetness of the marmalade was spot on! This was an unforgettable dish, and I have yet to encounter another cut that tastes as great as this one. My mouth is salivating just writing this. For dessert, we ordered the Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces. We ordered it during the beginning of the meal because it takes extra time to prepare. The presentation and flavor of this dessert was A+. They pour the two sauces into the soufflé right in front of you. Definitely recommend if you have a sweet tooth. But that's not all! After the meal, the servers provided us with a take-home treat. Ours was a pumpkin cheesecake pastry, that was delicious! You can tell how much time and effort everyone at the restaurant dedicates to making the experience memorable and unique. If you are looking for a special experience in San Francisco with delicious food, impressive service, and a relaxing vibe, then Gary Danko is your place.

With the recent onslaught of instagrammable high end dining spots like Lazy Bear and Benu, Gary Danko seems to be a forgotten memory. It's been a decade since the last time I've been here, but I'm 100% happy to report that nothing has changed since my first time here. Reservations are still tough to get, but since I'm an early eater these days, we arrived at opening and happen to score a romantic corner table since a later reservation was running late. For those seeking a luxurious dinner where diners freely choose between three, four or five courses and allowing to mix and match for a relatively reasonable price, this restaurant still satisfies in all levels. Impeccable seafood, fabulous MMMeat dishes, uber fresh appetizers and delectable desserts graze menu choices. The fine lobster claw atop a silky potato puree, perfectly cooked beef tenderloin, mouth watering lemon pepper duck and the endless mignardises all please to no end. Of course, I had to get their famous soufflé presented tableside, a Grand Marnier Version with vanilla anglaise and blood orange sorbet. Sweetly delicious down to the last bite. The notable wine list is not to be missed, as are the cocktails. Service is top notch and warm. All in all, Gary Danko is still unsurpassed in all categories and checks off all the right boxes. A fantastic, special occasion restaurant you should (re)consider when looking to impress your loved one.

    Meh.  Finally dined here again this weekend after my first visit over a decade ago.  Friends convinced me to give it another try, and well... meh.  I chose the 3 courses for $92 (which is $125 with tax, mandatory health surcharge and tip), and two of my friends ordered the 5 courses with the third friend option for 4 courses.  Both of the 5 course orderers had said that the staff usually brings out a little something for the non-course-orderers so you're not just sitting there staring at other people eat.  We'll get back to that.

    Third course, nothing for me but I got fresh silverware for no reason, and just sat there while my friends ate.  Very awkward.

    Fourth course, I got "Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive and Huckleberry Bordelaise" (again, pasting from the web site but my menu at the restaurant said cherries instead of huckleberry).  Outstanding dish.  Perfectly cooked duck, and I love the hash.  I had this dish last time and loved it then as well.

    Overall, I was really let down, especially given the large price tag.  I was made to feel quite awkward because I didn't order the same number of courses, and I don't understand why I didn't even receive the same quality of dish as my friend.  Service was extremely slow, and I really did not appreciate the snide comment about "no dessert for you".  I did not raise any issues at the time because this was my friend's birthday dinner, but I won't be returning here (despite that amazing duck dish).

    11/27/2008Previous review

    I've been waiting to go to Restaurant Gary Danko for years, and finally made it there a few weeks ago to celebrate our anniversary (and posting this as my 300th Yelp review!). Unfortunately, it did not live up to my expectations.

    We arrived early, having found parking on the street nearby, and were promptly seated (which was much appreciated). I sat along the banquette, and my husband sat facing me. He later told me that he was constantly bumped by servers throughout the entire meal. Though our server (a friendly woman) came over quickly to take our drink order, she soon vanished. Someone brought us an amuse of a creamy soup while were looking over the menu. Another server, a male with perhaps a French accent, later returned and apparently was there to take our dinner order. He was not very friendly and did not offer much help (and never returned).

    I had scoured the menu online and knew things that sounded great - oddly, the menu was slightly different depending on if you were viewing it on their Flash version of their web site or the HTML version. One thing that jumped out to me was: "Risotto with Lobster, Laughing Bird Shrimp, Corn, Butternut Squash, Parmigiano-Reggiano and Basil Oil". At the restaurant, the item was listed without the lobster, oddly. I went ahead and ordered it as my starter. It was okay - the rice was actually a bit too crunchy for my taste. Though I liked the shrimp, I would've really liked the lobster as mentioned online.

    My husband started with "Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelles, Corn and Tarragon". The lobster was tiny - we've have prawns larger than this lobster! It was a little under-cooked but was fine. The mushrooms were really tasty.

    For our main dishes, I had "Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celery Root-Garlic Purée and Cardamom Poached Pears". This was really good - the duck breast portion was nice and cooked perfectly. The hash was a little disk of fried goodness (the spices reminded me of haggis, in a good way). The pears were really good but maybe two tablespoons' worth.

    My husband had the "Seared Filet of Beef with Potato Gratin, Cassis Glazed Shallots and Blue Cheese Butter". The gratin was great, the shallot were okay. The butter was served on the side as requested. The filet, unfortunately, was completely overcooked. And even more unfortunately, no one came by our table for a long time. He had finished everything else on his plate and only had a couple bites of the meat left by the time our server *finally* came by (I had finished my dish by then). The server apologized and offered to remake the filet, but my husband didn't want to wait yet longer. The manager came over and apologized, saying this so rarely happens and said she'd take the dish off the bill.

    We followed this with the cheese course (shared). Our server explained all the cheeses and we chose a few, which were accompanied by a handful of grapes and two slices of raisin bread. I don't remember the cheeses we had, but the server did write them down for us and had a card waiting for us at the front desk as we left. Two of the cheeses were very soft, and we desperately wanted some extra bread (plain bread, what we had during the meal). Again, we couldn't get ahold of any server to help. We waited at least ten minutes before finally getting someone's attention and receiving a few extra small slices of plain bread for the cheese.

    Lastly, we shared the chocolate souffle. It came with two sauces, both poured in by the server. The souffle was cooked perfectly and looked gorgeous and very tasty. Moments later, our server brought out a small slice of a frozen passionfruit mousse with a slim candle for our anniversary. It also was tasty and a nice counterpoint to the chocolate. A few minutes later, our server returned with a small silver tray of tiny bites of assorted sweets. A nice touch.

    At the end of our meal, I was given a small pumpkin muffin for later. When we got the bill, I was surprised to see that my husband's meal was $9 less than mine, which surprised me. I appreciated the generosity of taking off his filet, but $9 off the $66 meal was surprising. The lobster starter was billed at $36! After a quick conference with the manager, the bill was adjusted a little more (I didn't know the final amount as husband took care of it while I was waiting for the restroom).

    Overall, I was really let down. I had such high hopes, especially having read so many glowing reviews on Yelp. The service was not good during our visit. Our server was hard to find and the staff in general didn't seem interested in us (perhaps because we didn't order wine?). We shouldn't have had to wait forever for someone to check in with us. I noticed the party next to us also had difficulty getting our server when they needed help too - he had to flag down three staff members to get a box for his dessert. I so very much wanted this to be a fantastic experience, but instead we were left wanting.

    This is not your everyday restaurant. But at the same time, not bad for a special occasion.

    Went here for a 3rd year wedding anniversary and for two people with wine tasting, I spent close to $500 including tips! Oh they even have us a take home bread pudding which we savoured for breakfast the next morning!

    What I love about this place is you aren't tied to a pre fix. You are free to choose from a different selection from their menu so it gives it more flexibility for you to order what you want.

    10/31/2019

    2 check-ins

    This was my second time at Gary Danko and this time my husband surprised me with a dinner here for my birthday.  This is more 3.5 stars but I decided to round down to 3 stars.

    PARKING: We came on a Sunday night around 8pm and there was some decent street parking.  I think if you circle around and try to find something you'll be fine.

    RESERVATIONS: My husband made the reservations but he said he made them about a month in advance and even then he could only get a 8:30 reservation for 2.

    ATMOSPHERE: Gary Danko has a lot of reviews and supposedly 1 michelin star but the inside is pretty old/traditional looking.  Don't expect your super contemporary, trendy atmosphere.  It's dark lit, roses on the table, highly attentive waiters and a weird decor ranging from sea theme to jungle?  Overall, not the type of atmosphere I particularly like but it's certainly fancy and romantic.

    FOOD: They have these "set" menus where you can choose whatever you want and pay a set price.  For example, if you choose the 3 course dinner you pay $95.  You could do whatever you want, which means 3 desserts, 3 appetizers, 3 entrees etc.  I would suggest coordinating with your other party so you can all try different items.  Their portions aren't huge but aren't super tiny either.  You are given an amuse bouche to begin with and then unlimited bread and butter.  They also give you a small dessert tray with mini desserts and a take home pastry.  So in the end, you're getting more than just the 3 entrees.

    I'm sure their menu changes all the time so I won't go into specifics but I would say everything we had was good. Nothing mind blowing, nothing bad...just good.  I think that's why I decided on 3.5 stars.  The price I'm paying and what I was expecting I was hoping for a bit more or something more memorable.

    Overall, if you like fancy restaurants and the $95 fee per person doesn't shock you then definitely give this place a try.

    ROTD 10/12/2019

    I'm drooling about the food while writing this review.  My bf booked this place in advance for my birthday since I've been wanting to try it in forever. We decided to get the 5 course meal for $135. What's amazing is that you can choose your own five selections from wherever area you want. If you want all meat... you can do all meat. If you want meat, fish, appetizer, dessert, and cheese... you can do that.

    Rose wine - They only had one rose wine by the glass on the menu. It was a 2017 rose wine from Napa. It was very tasty, and not crazy sweet. Highly recommend.

    Glazed oysters (appetizer) - Comes with four oysters and cavier in the middle. The sauce pairs extremely well with the oysters and the cavier is a finishing touch. I really enjoyed this appetizer.

    Dungeness crab salad (appetizer) - The crab was really fresh and the leafy greens were a great light start to the meal.

    Roast maine lobster (fish and seafood) - If I had known that this was so good, I would've skipped the duck breast and Dungeness crab salad and got three of these. This dish is a definitely must get! You won't regret it.

    Lemon pepper duck breast (meat and game birds) - To be honest, I'm not a duck person so I have no idea why I got this. They gave a generous portion, and it was cooked nicely. If you like duck, you'd probably appreciate this dish more than I would.

    Strawberry souffle (dessert) - The top part of this is very tasty, but once you get to the middle, it's mostly sauce and it's too sweet. I'd probably skip dessert next time or try the cookies.

    Service was beyond impeccable and my plate was never empty of their delicious bread. I think I had 6 pieces which is why I got so full after my third item.

    Gary Danko is a lovely place, and I'd definitely be back!

    Gary Danko provides one of the greatest fine-dining experiences in San Francisco. The chefs and servers are thoughtful and masters at what they do. The way the food is served is like a performance! The restaurant ambiance is dimly lit and very intimate--perfect for any special occasion.

    I ordered the Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes and Swiss Chard. The filet was topped with blue cheese butter and a sweet marmalade. Let me tell you...this was THE BEST filet that I have ever had in my life! The meat was incredibly flavorful and tender--it cut like butter. I do not regularly enjoy blue cheese, but the combination of flavors with the beef and the sweetness of the marmalade was spot on! This was an unforgettable dish, and I have yet to encounter another cut that tastes as great as this one. My mouth is salivating just writing this.

    For dessert, we ordered the Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces. We ordered it during the beginning of the meal because it takes extra time to prepare. The presentation and flavor of this dessert was A+. They pour the two sauces into the soufflé right in front of you. Definitely recommend if you have a sweet tooth.

    But that's not all!

    After the meal, the servers provided us with a take-home treat. Ours was a pumpkin cheesecake pastry, that was delicious!

    You can tell how much time and effort everyone at the restaurant dedicates to making the experience memorable and unique. If you are looking for a special experience in San Francisco with delicious food, impressive service, and a relaxing vibe, then Gary Danko is your place.

    With the recent onslaught of instagrammable high end dining spots like Lazy Bear and Benu, Gary Danko seems to be a forgotten memory.

    It's been a decade since the last time I've been here, but I'm 100% happy to report that nothing has changed since my first time here. Reservations are still tough to get, but since I'm an early eater these days, we arrived at opening and happen to score a romantic corner table since a later reservation was running late.

    For those seeking a luxurious dinner where diners freely choose between three, four or five courses and allowing to mix and match for a relatively reasonable price, this restaurant still satisfies in all levels. Impeccable seafood, fabulous MMMeat dishes, uber fresh appetizers and delectable desserts graze menu choices. The fine lobster claw atop a silky potato puree, perfectly cooked beef tenderloin, mouth watering lemon pepper duck and the endless mignardises all please to no end. Of course, I had to get their famous soufflé presented tableside, a Grand Marnier Version with vanilla anglaise and blood orange sorbet. Sweetly delicious down to the last bite.

    The notable wine list is not to be missed, as are the cocktails. Service is top notch and warm.

    All in all, Gary Danko is still unsurpassed in all categories and checks off all the right boxes. A fantastic, special occasion restaurant you should (re)consider when looking to impress your loved one.

    Color me impressed!

    Gary Danko put SF on the map, not the Golden Gate bridge. He woos you with his army of staff who will cater to your every need. They anticipate it even before you could think it.  From the hostess, who immediately offers to take your coat, to servers who constantly refill your bread plate, replace your silverware, fold your napkins when you leave the table, open bathroom doors for you and our waiter who even offered to call a cab if we needed one at the end of our meal.  All that pampering made me feel like a princess, I just needed a personal slave to feed me grapes off my cheese plate!

    Actually, let me rephrase that.  I wouldn't mind being Danko's slave.  

    Like Britney Spears said, I'm a slave for you.

    I will scrub your pots and pans until the bottom shone, in exchange for your seared foie gras with caramelized apples.  It was so indulgent, so sinfully rich on the tongue.

    I will hand wash and iron your finest table linens, in exchange for your succulent, sweet, perfectly roasted Maine lobster with chanterelle mushrooms, edamame and creamy mashed potatoes.

    I will spit polish your silverware with painstaking patience, in exchange for your creamy lobster risotto with butternut squash, corn and tomatoes.

    I will mop your floors with organic cleaners, in exchange for your thoughtfully chosen cheese plate, which not only has my fave Brillat savarin triple creme, but also has excellent Humboldt Fog goat cheese and a pleasant Roaring 40's blue cheese.

    I will sort out your recyclables and compact your trash for you, in exchange for your wonderful chocolate souffle with its sweet creme anglaise and chocolate sauce.
